[2 bladen] Ad [Addendum] 35. [blad 1, recto] British Museum Printroom. [A.E.] Popham 12 [= Catalogue of drawings by Dutch and Flemish artists preserved in the department of prints and drawings in the British Museum, V: V : Dutch and Flemish drawings of the XV and XVI centuries, London: British Museum, 1932], p. 147, NÂ° 13 Three Blind Pilgrims 1910-2-12-124 Vasari Soc. VIII, 21 [...] ; [blad 1, verso] [...] Important for Bruegel's continued occupation with the [onderstreept] Blind, not only in the Proverbs but perhaps also interest in the poor and ailing [onleesbaar] [...]; [blad 2] Addendum Popham B. Was the original a drawing or a painting? The form of the signature (copied) speaks for drawing. Therefore this copy is to be considered among the drawings of 1566. It was probably the design for a painting, in its monumentality cf. Adulteress of 1565.
